[
  {
    "client_msg_id": "F24A5688-126F-4527-9825-499935155815",
    "type": "message",
    "text": "Been thinking about this framing of how programing languages are these higher dimensional entities that we interact with though a textual projection that has limited dimensions to interact with. Visual programming languages are means to interact with with programming languages with more dimensions. \n\nJumps (and other control flow like loops and branches that try to hide jumps) are one example of where this projection happens since text is sequential and allows us to link non-sequntial code into sequences.\n\n“Dimensions” is being used very loosley here, im not sure how to define it, but its not necessarily physical dimensions. For example, maybe i would consider function stacks its own dimension that is textually hard to understand (<https://twitter.com/ShriramKMurthi/status/1545039706148278272?s=20&amp;t=CeAb-qrq-XtE7nfXoxWsGA|https://twitter.com/ShriramKMurthi/status/1545039706148278272?s=20&amp;t=CeAb-qrq-XtE7nfXoxWsGA>). It’s interesting to think about what dimensions we are adding to visual programming languages and how they change our understanding of the software we write!\n\n(For more <morehttps://twitter.com/chrisshank23/status/1544946015903502337?s=20&amp;t=Ps17TClKA_8AryeeU58uOA|https://twitter.com/chrisshank23/status/1544946015903502337?s=20&amp;t=Ps17TClKA_8AryeeU58uOA>)",
